As julie wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/16/2004 at 00:50:19 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>How do u rationalize a problem with sin x, cos x, or tan x in the 
>denominator for example 1/(1-cos x) 
>
>[Difficulty]
>the directions read as follows "Remove the sum or difference for the 
>denominator by multiplying the numerator and denominator by the 
>conjugate of the denominator."
>
>[Thoughts]
>(1/(1-cos x))*((1+cos x)/(1+cos x))

Thanks for writing to Ask Dr. Math, Julie!

Your thoughts are right on target!  Multiply this out, and then use
the fact that sin^2(x) + cos^2(x) = 1.

Feel free to reply if I can help further with this question.


